vlanCMMTableCacheTimeout.name: vlanCMMTableCacheTimeout
vlanCMMTableCacheTimeout.description: The timeout value (in seconds) of the cached data for the table, vlanCMMTable. This value is static (constant) and cannot be set.

snmpSystemContact.name: snmpSystemContact
snmpSystemContact.description: A NULL terminated 48 byte string that contains the SNMP agent contact name.

snmpSystemLocation.name: snmpSystemLocation
snmpSystemLocation.description: A NULL terminated 48 byte string that contains the SNMP agent location name.

snmpCommunityEntryIndex.name: snmpCommunityEntryIndex
snmpCommunityEntryIndex.description: Index for SNMP Agent Community entry.

snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress1.name: snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress1
snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress1.description: SNMP Community IP address or host name. Can either be a dotted decimal IP string (e.g. 9.37.44.2) or if DNS is enabled a host name. This field also allows two wildard values for read-Traps and write-Read-Traps communities: 0.0.0.0 - allow any IPv4 address 0::0 - allow any IPv6 address

snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress2.name: snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress2
snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress2.description: SNMP Community IP address or host name. Can either be a dotted decimal IP string (e.g. 9.37.44.2) or if DNS is enabled a host name. This field also allows two wildard values for read-Traps and write-Read-Traps communities: 0.0.0.0 - allow any IPv4 address 0::0 - allow any IPv6 address

snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress3.name: snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress3
snmpCommunityEntryCommunityIpAddress3.description: SNMP Community IP address or host name. Can either be a dotted decimal IP string (e.g. 9.37.44.2) or if DNS is enabled a host name. This field also allows two wildard values for read-Traps and write-Read-Traps communities: 0.0.0.0 - allow any IPv4 address 0::0 - allow any IPv6 address

snmpCommunityEntryCommunityViewType.name: snmpCommunityEntryCommunityViewType
snmpCommunityEntryCommunityViewType.description: Access Level of the SNMPv1 managers. Note this parameter is set for each community. Therefore all three managers in the same community have the same access level.

snmpv1SystemAgentEnable.name: snmpv1SystemAgentEnable
snmpv1SystemAgentEnable.description: Disable or enable the SNMPv1 agent. NOTE: Restart the management module if this MIB object is changed with respect to the value at system bootup time. For example the SNMPv1 agent was set to disabled at system bootup time and now it is enabled. Then restarting the remote supervisor is required. Also note that when attempting to enable this agent, the following are verified: (1) Is there a valid system contact (2) Is there a valid system name (3) Is there at least one valid community name and for that community name is there one valid IP address or hostname (4) Are all defined community names unique If this verification fails an error response will be returned and the SNMPv1 agent will be left disabled.

snmpv3SystemAgentEnable.name: snmpv3SystemAgentEnable
snmpv3SystemAgentEnable.description: Disable or enable the SNMPv3 agent. NOTE: Restart the management module if this MIB object is changed with respect to the value at system bootup time. For example the SNMPv3 agent was set to disabled at system bootup time and now it is enabled. Then restarting the remote supervisor is required. Also note that when attempting to enable this agent, the following are verified: (1) Is there a valid system contact? (2) Is there a valid system name? If this verification fails an error response will be returned and the SNMPv3 agent will be left disabled.

snmpUserProfileTable.name: snmpUserProfileTable
snmpUserProfileTable.description: Table of SNMPv3 User Profile entries

snmpUserProfileEntryIndex.name: snmpUserProfileEntryIndex
snmpUserProfileEntryIndex.description: Index for SNMPv3 Agent User Profile entry.

snmpUserProfileEntryContextName.name: snmpUserProfileEntryContextName
snmpUserProfileEntryContextName.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - Context name for users to access MIB objects. Note that context names can be duplicates and can be shared among users. Empty context names are allowed. The default context name is the empty string.

snmpUserProfileEntryAuthProt.name: snmpUserProfileEntryAuthProt
snmpUserProfileEntryAuthProt.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - Authentication Protocol supported by the user.

snmpUserProfileEntryPrivProt.name: snmpUserProfileEntryPrivProt
snmpUserProfileEntryPrivProt.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - Privacy Protocol supported by the user. The Privacy Password must be set and the Authentication Protocol must be md5 or sha before this field may be set to des or aes.

snmpUserProfileEntryPrivPassword.name: snmpUserProfileEntryPrivPassword
snmpUserProfileEntryPrivPassword.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - Privacy password for the user. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object for security reasons.

snmpUserProfileEntryViewType.name: snmpUserProfileEntryViewType
snmpUserProfileEntryViewType.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - Access level (Get, Set, and Traps) of the user.

snmpUserProfileEntryIpAddress.name: snmpUserProfileEntryIpAddress
snmpUserProfileEntryIpAddress.description: SNMPv3 User Profile entry - IP address or host name. Can either be a dotted decimal IP string (e.g. 9.37.44.2) or if DNS is enabled a host name.

snmpUserProfileEntryUserId.name: snmpUserProfileEntryUserId
snmpUserProfileEntryUserId.description: The userid for the SNMPv3 Agent User Profile entry.

dnsEnabled.name: dnsEnabled
dnsEnabled.description: Disable or enable the DNS agent. NOTE: To alter any of the configuration settings for the DNS agent, the following procedure should be used: (1) This object should be set to 'disabled' (2) Make the modifications to other settings (3) This object should be set to 'enabled' Also note that when attempting to enable this agent, it is verified that there is at least one valid DNS server IP address. If this verification fails, an error response will be returned and the DNS agent will be left disabled.

dnsServerIPAddress1.name: dnsServerIPAddress1
dnsServerIPAddress1.description: Contains the primary DNS server IP address.

dnsServerIPAddress2.name: dnsServerIPAddress2
dnsServerIPAddress2.description: Contains the secondary DNS server IP address.

dnsServerIPAddress3.name: dnsServerIPAddress3
dnsServerIPAddress3.description: Contains the tertiary DNS server IP address.

dnsServerIPv6Address1.name: dnsServerIPv6Address1
dnsServerIPv6Address1.description: Contains the primary IPv6 DNS server address.

dnsServerIPv6Address2.name: dnsServerIPv6Address2
dnsServerIPv6Address2.description: Contains the secondary IPv6 DNS server address.

dnsServerIPv6Address3.name: dnsServerIPv6Address3
dnsServerIPv6Address3.description: Contains the tertiary IPv6 DNS server address.

dnsPriority.name: dnsPriority
dnsPriority.description: Tells the order host names are resolved. The options are to either first resolve with an IPv6 DNS server or to first resolve with an IPv6 DNS server.

smtpServerNameOrIPAddress.name: smtpServerNameOrIPAddress
smtpServerNameOrIPAddress.description: A NULL terminated 64 byte string that contains the SMTP server host name or IP address (a.b.c.d).

attachmentsToEmailAlerts.name: attachmentsToEmailAlerts
attachmentsToEmailAlerts.description: Indicates if the service information should be attached to an email alert.

smtpEmailDomain.name: smtpEmailDomain
smtpEmailDomain.description: A NULL terminated string that contains the SMTP email domain. If this field is empty, the MM IP address is used as the domain. However, some SMTP servers (e.g. - MS Exchange 2007) do not accept an IP address and instead require a domain name. This object can be used to set that email domain name.

telnetInactivityTimeout.name: telnetInactivityTimeout
telnetInactivityTimeout.description: Default is 120 seconds. Value of zero is no timeout. Max value is any positive 4 bytes value. Note that SSH also uses this timeout value to wait before disconnecting inactive SSH connections.

commandModeInactivityTimeout.name: commandModeInactivityTimeout
commandModeInactivityTimeout.description: The amount of time in seconds before the (Secure)TCP Command Mode times out. Default value of 0 means no timeout. Max value is any positive 4 byte value.

secureCommandModeEnable.name: secureCommandModeEnable
secureCommandModeEnable.description: Set Secure TCP Command Mode number of connections. MM will provide a max of 20 connections for both Secure TCP Command Mode and TCP Command Mode. A value of 0 means disabled. If no valid server certificate is in place, Secure TCP Command Mode will not be allowed to set to enable.

commandModeEnable.name: commandModeEnable
commandModeEnable.description: Set TCP Command Mode number of connections. MM will provide a max of 20 connections for both Secure TCP Command Mode and TCP Command Mode. A value of 0 means disabled.

slpAddrType.name: slpAddrType
slpAddrType.description: Set SLP address type to 0 (multicast) or 1 (broadcast). Note that when slpAddrType is set to broadcast value then the multicast address set in slpMulticastAddr will be ignored.

slpEnable.name: slpEnable
slpEnable.description: Disable/Enable Service Location Protocol. NOTE: Change to Service Location Protocol will take effect after the next restart of the MM.

telnetEnable.name: telnetEnable
telnetEnable.description: Disable/Enable telnet. NOTE: Change to telnet enable/disable will take effect immediately.

sslClientEnable.name: sslClientEnable
sslClientEnable.description: Disable/Enable SSL Client. If no valid client or server certificate is in place, SSL client will not be allowed to set to enable.

ftpTimeout.name: ftpTimeout
ftpTimeout.description: The amount of time before FTP times out. Default is 300 seconds. Value of zero is no timeout. Max value is any positive 4 byte value.

cimEnable.name: cimEnable
cimEnable.description: Disable/Enable CIM (Common Information Model) interface. NOTE: Change to CIM enable/disable will take effect immediately.

mmSshServerHostKeyTable.name: mmSshServerHostKeyTable
mmSshServerHostKeyTable.description: A table that contains per public/private host key pair information.

mmSshServerHostKeyEntry.name: mmSshServerHostKeyEntry
mmSshServerHostKeyEntry.description: A list of information about a particular public/private host key pair.

mmSshServerHostKeyIndex.name: mmSshServerHostKeyIndex
mmSshServerHostKeyIndex.description: The index of the public/private host key pair.

mmSshServerHostKeyType.name: mmSshServerHostKeyType
mmSshServerHostKeyType.description: The type of the public/private host key pair.

mmSshServerHostKeySize.name: mmSshServerHostKeySize
mmSshServerHostKeySize.description: The size of the public/private host key pair. NOTE: The MM supports only the bits2048 value.

mmSshServerHostKeyFingerprint.name: mmSshServerHostKeyFingerprint
mmSshServerHostKeyFingerprint.description: The RSA fingerprint of the public part of the host key pair. This value can be used with the SSH client to verify, on the initial connection, that the Secure Shell server responding to the request is the server running on the MM.

mmSshServerHostKeyGenerate.name: mmSshServerHostKeyGenerate
mmSshServerHostKeyGenerate.description: Initiate the new Host Keys generation process for the MM SSH Server. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

mmSshServerHostKeyGenerateProgress.name: mmSshServerHostKeyGenerateProgress
mmSshServerHostKeyGenerateProgress.description: Indicate the progress of the key generation process.

tcpPortsRestoreDefault.name: tcpPortsRestoreDefault
tcpPortsRestoreDefault.description: Reset all ports to default value. http: 80 https: 443 telnet: 23 ssh: 22 SNMP agent: 161 SNMP trap: 162 TCP Command Mode: 6090 Secure TCP Command Mode: 6091 FTP: 21 FTP Data: 20 TFTP: 69 SLP: 427 CIM: 5989 NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

httpPortAssignment.name: httpPortAssignment
httpPortAssignment.description: HTTP port number. Default value is 80. Once changed, the URL's have to include :port at the end.

httpsPortAssignment.name: httpsPortAssignment
httpsPortAssignment.description: SSL port number. Default value is 443. Once changed, the URL's have to include :port at the end.

telnetPortAssignment.name: telnetPortAssignment
telnetPortAssignment.description: Telnet port number. Default value is 23. Port change will take effect immediately.

sshPortAssignment.name: sshPortAssignment
sshPortAssignment.description: SSH port number. Default value is 22.

snmpAgentPortAssignment.name: snmpAgentPortAssignment
snmpAgentPortAssignment.description: SNMP Agent port number. Default value is 161. Changes take effect after several seconds.

snmpTrapsPortAssignment.name: snmpTrapsPortAssignment
snmpTrapsPortAssignment.description: SNMP Traps port number. Default value is 162. Changes take effect after several seconds.

commandModePortAssignment.name: commandModePortAssignment
commandModePortAssignment.description: TCP Command Mode port number. Default value is 6090. Change will take effect immediately.

secureCommandModePortAssignment.name: secureCommandModePortAssignment
secureCommandModePortAssignment.description: Secure TCP Command Mode port number. Default value is 6091. Change will take effect immediately.

ftpPortAssignment.name: ftpPortAssignment
ftpPortAssignment.description: FTP port number. Default value is 21. Port change will take effect immediately.

ftpDataPortAssignment.name: ftpDataPortAssignment
ftpDataPortAssignment.description: FTP Data port number. Default value is 20. Port change will take effect immediately.

tftpPortAssignment.name: tftpPortAssignment
tftpPortAssignment.description: TFTP port number. Default value is 69.

slpPortAssignment.name: slpPortAssignment
slpPortAssignment.description: Service Location Protocol port number. Default value is 427. NOTE: This value is normally required to be 427 to interoperate properly with other SLP enabled applications.

cimPortAssignment.name: cimPortAssignment
cimPortAssignment.description: CIM (Common Information Model) port number. Default value is 5989. Port change will take effect immediately.

ldapServer1NameOrIPAddress.name: ldapServer1NameOrIPAddress
ldapServer1NameOrIPAddress.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the LDAP server host name or IP address (a.b.c.d).

ldapServer2NameOrIPAddress.name: ldapServer2NameOrIPAddress
ldapServer2NameOrIPAddress.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the LDAP server host name or IP address (a.b.c.d).

ldapServer3NameOrIPAddress.name: ldapServer3NameOrIPAddress
ldapServer3NameOrIPAddress.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the LDAP server host name or IP address (a.b.c.d).

ldapRootDN.name: ldapRootDN
ldapRootDN.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the distinguished Name for root entry of directory tree. An example might look like dn=foobar,dn=com.

ldapGroupFilter.name: ldapGroupFilter
ldapGroupFilter.description: This filter is used for group authentication. It specifies what group or groups that this MM belongs to. If left blank, group authentication is disabled. Otherwise, group authentication will be performed against the filter. The filter can be a specific group name (e.g. RSAWest), a wildcard (*) which matches everything, or a wildcard with a prefix (e.g. RSA*). The default filter is RSA*. After user authentication, group authentication will take place, whereby an attempt will be made to match the group or groups (that the user belongs to) to the group filter defined here. If there is no match, the user will not pass authentication and will be blocked. If there is a match, the login permissions for the user will be retrieved from the matched group(s), unless the user already has login permissions assigned directly from the user record retrieved from the LDAP server.

ldapBindingMethod.name: ldapBindingMethod
ldapBindingMethod.description: On initial binds to the LDAP server during user authentication, there are two options: Client authentication: Bind attempt is made with client DN and password specified by this configuration parameter. If the bind is successful, we proceed as above. User Principal Name (UPN): Bind attempt is made directly with the credentials used during the login process. If this succeeds, the user is deemed to have passed the user authentication phase. Note that for Active Directory servers, the userid can have the form someuser@somedomain or simply someuser.

ldapClientAuthenticationDN.name: ldapClientAuthenticationDN
ldapClientAuthenticationDN.description: The initial bind to the LDAP server during user authentication can be performed with anonymous authentication, client based authentication, or UPN. The client based option requires a client DN and password as parameters to the bind request. These parameters are configured here. Note that the password can be left blank.

ldapUIDsearchAttribute.name: ldapUIDsearchAttribute
ldapUIDsearchAttribute.description: When the binding method selected is Anonymous authentication or Client authentication, the initial bind to the LDAP server is followed by a search request aimed at retrieving specific information about the user, including the user's DN, login permissions, and group ownerships. In order to retrieve this information, the search request must specify the attribute name used to represent userids on that server. Specifically, this name is used as a search filter against the login id entered by the user. This attribute name is configured here. If this field is left blank, a default of uid is used during user authentication. For example, on Active Directory servers, the attribute name used for userids is often sAMAccoutName. When the binding method selected is UPN or Strict UPN, this field defaults automatically to userPrincipalName during user authentication if the userid entered has the form userid@somedomain.

ldapGroupSearchAttribute.name: ldapGroupSearchAttribute
ldapGroupSearchAttribute.description: When the MM Group Filter name is configured, it is necessary to retrieve from the LDAP server the list of groups that a particular user belongs to. This is required to do group authentication. In order to retrieve this list, the search filter sent to the server must specify the attribute name associated with groups. This field specifies this attribute name. If this field is left blank, the attribute name in the filter will default to memberOf.

ldapLoginPermissionAttribute.name: ldapLoginPermissionAttribute
ldapLoginPermissionAttribute.description: When a user successfully authenticates via a LDAP server, it is necessary to retrieve the login permissions for this user. In order to retrieve these permissions, the search filter sent to the server must specify the attribute name associated with login permissions. This field specifies this attribute name.

ldapUseDNSOrPreConfiguredServers.name: ldapUseDNSOrPreConfiguredServers
ldapUseDNSOrPreConfiguredServers.description: The MM contains a Version 2.0 LDAP Client that may be configured to provide user authentication through one or more LDAP servers. The LDAP server(s) to be used for authentication can be discovered dynamically or manually pre-configured. If the usePreConfiguredLDAPServers option is selected, up to 4 LDAP servers can be configured. Simply enter the server's IP address or hostname (assuming DNS is enabled). The port number for each server is optional. If left blank, the default value of 389 is used for non-secured LDAP connections. For secured connections, the default is 636. At least one server must be configured. If the useDNSToFindLDAPServers is selected, the domain name need to be provided. For LDAP Authentication Only mode, additional information such as the forest name also need to be provided.

ldapRBSModelCfg.name: ldapRBSModelCfg
ldapRBSModelCfg.description: There are two mechanisms to authenticate and authorize users on the MM when using an LDAP-enabled server. The first mechanism (oldPermissionString), also known as version 1, uses bitstrings to associate permissions to users and groups. Version1 supports Active Directory, Novell eDirectory, and OPenLDAP based servers. The second mechanism (newRBSModel), also known as version 2, uses a new Role-Based-Security (RBS) model. This mechanism is only available for Active Directory servers, and requires the use of a snap-in that runs on any windows platform. This snap-in tool allows you to configure roles on an Active Directory server of your choice, and to associate users/groups and MMs to those roles. A role identifies the permissions given to users and groups associated with that role, and also identifies the targets (e.g. MM) to which this role is attached. The use of bitstrings in version 2 disappears, making the configuration much more manageable and user-friendly. Note that if you are not using Active Directory, then you should not enable version 2. Also note that before enabling version 2, you should already have your roles configured on your Active Directory server. The old version 1 bitstring model cannot be automatically converted to the new version 2 model. This is why you must configure your users and groups before enabling version 2. Once enabled, the change takes effect immediately. The default value for this field is oldPermissionString.

ldapTargetName.name: ldapTargetName
ldapTargetName.description: When administrator chooses Enhanced Role Based Security authentication model, he can associate one MM with one managed target object in Snap-in (one tool to configure LDAP users permission) via one target name. The MM target name can be looked as alias of MM, administrator can change it according to his configuration requirements. This is a string of up to 63 characters (plus the null character)

ldapAuthCfg.name: ldapAuthCfg
ldapAuthCfg.description: If ldapAuthCfg is set to 0, LDAP server is used to authenticate and authorize users. If it is set to 1, LDAP server is only used to authenticate users. Note:LDAP Authentication Only mode is currently supported only in an Active Directory environment.

ldapForestName.name: ldapForestName
ldapForestName.description: LDAP Forest Name. Note: LDAP Forest Name is only for Active Directory environment.

ldapDomainName.name: ldapDomainName
ldapDomainName.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the LDAP Domain Name.

ldapServer4NameOrIPAddress.name: ldapServer4NameOrIPAddress
ldapServer4NameOrIPAddress.description: A NULL terminated 255 byte string that contains the LDAP server host name or IP address (a.b.c.d).

uplinkCheckEnabled.name: uplinkCheckEnabled
uplinkCheckEnabled.description: Disable or enable network uplink checking for physical detection. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

uplinkCheckDelay.name: uplinkCheckDelay
uplinkCheckDelay.description: Delay, in minutes (1-2880), between discovery of a failed network uplink and the subsequent MM failover for physical detection. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkDestination.name: logicalUplinkDestination
logicalUplinkDestination.description: Destination IP for MM to check its logical link. Specify a non-zero IP Address in order to enable logical uplink checking. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkCheckEnabled.name: logicalUplinkCheckEnabled
logicalUplinkCheckEnabled.description: Disable or enable network uplink checking for logical detection. logicalUplinkDestination must be set to a non-zero IP Address before enable logical uplink checking. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkCheckDelay.name: logicalUplinkCheckDelay
logicalUplinkCheckDelay.description: Delay, in minutes(1-2880), between discovery of a failed network uplink and the subsequent MM failover for logical detection. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

physicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs.name: physicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs
physicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs.description: Delay, in seconds(10-172800), between discovery of a failed network uplink and the subsequent MM failover for physical detection. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs.name: logicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs
logicalUplinkCheckDelayInSecs.description: Delay, in seconds(60-172800), between discovery of a failed network uplink and the subsequent MM failover for logical detection. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkIPv6Destination.name: logicalUplinkIPv6Destination
logicalUplinkIPv6Destination.description: Destination IP for MM to check its logical link using IPv6. Specify a non-zero IP Address in order to enable logical uplink checking. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

logicalUplinkFailoverPolicy.name: logicalUplinkFailoverPolicy
logicalUplinkFailoverPolicy.description: Determines when to failover if both an IPv4 and IPv6 destination have been configured. If set to 'either' the system will failover if either of the destination's link check fails. If set to 'both' then the IPv4 and IPv6 link checks must fail before a failover will happen. NOTE: This MIB object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

ntpEnable.name: ntpEnable
ntpEnable.description: Disable/Enable the NTP client. The client will update the MM system clock at the frequency specified.

ntpIpAddressHostname.name: ntpIpAddressHostname
ntpIpAddressHostname.description: NTP server's IP address or hostname if DNS is enabled and configured.

ntpUpdateFrequency.name: ntpUpdateFrequency
ntpUpdateFrequency.description: The frequency in minutes that the NTP service runs. The value range is 0 to 45000. If the NTP update frequency is set to 0, the MM clock can only be synchronized with the NTP server manually.

ntpLastUpdate.name: ntpLastUpdate
ntpLastUpdate.description: The date and time that the NTP server last updated the system clock.

ntpUpdateClock.name: ntpUpdateClock
ntpUpdateClock.description: Update the MM system clock with the specified NTP server. A valid NTP server must be configured first.

ntpAuthEntry.name: ntpAuthEntry
ntpAuthEntry.description: The NTP v3 authentication entry to be used for time sync with a secure NTP server. The format of an authentication entry is <key index> <key type> <key>. <key index> must be an integer between 1 and 65535. <key type> must be M. <key> is the actual value of the authentication key as configured on the NTP server. The GET command returns back data in the format: <key index> <key type> It does not return the actual key.

syslogCollectorHostnameOrIpAddress.name: syslogCollectorHostnameOrIpAddress
syslogCollectorHostnameOrIpAddress.description: Syslog Collector IP address or host name.

syslogTestPacket.name: syslogTestPacket
syslogTestPacket.description: Generate a test syslog packet. This will send a test syslog to all configured and enabled syslog collectors to assist in validating the configuration. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

solAccumulateTimeout.name: solAccumulateTimeout
solAccumulateTimeout.description: This value specifies how much time in millisecond SOL to buffer data before sending the next SOL packet since the last SOL packet was transmitted. Valid value from 5 ms to 1275 ms. The value is in 5 ms increment. Value is not in 5 ms increment will be truncated to a nearest 5s. Default value is 5 ms.

solCharSendThreshold.name: solCharSendThreshold
solCharSendThreshold.description: This value specifies how many characters SOL to buffer before sending the next SOL packet since the last SOL packet was transmitted. Valid value is from 1 to 251

solRetry.name: solRetry
solRetry.description: Retry count. Valid value from 0-7. 0 means no retries after packet is transmitted. Packet will be dropped if no ACK/NACK received by the time retries expired.

solRetryInterval.name: solRetryInterval
solRetryInterval.description: Retry Interval in 10 ms increment. Sets the time that the SOL will wait before the first retry and the time between retries when sending SOL packets to the remote blade. Value range is from 0 to 2550 ms in 10 ms increment. 0 means retries will be sent back-to-back.

solExitToCliKeySeq.name: solExitToCliKeySeq
solExitToCliKeySeq.description: This is the keystroke sequence used to escape out of SOL session and back to CLI console. This sequence must have at least one character. The caret symbol (^) has a special meaning in this sequence. It denotes 'Ctrl' for keystrokes that map to Ctrl sequences (for example, ^[ for the escape key and ^M for carriage return). All occurrences of ^ will be interpreted as part of a Ctrl sequence. Refer to an ASCII-to-key conversion table for a complete list of Ctrl sequences. The default value for this field is '^[(' i.e. ESC followed by (.

solResetBladeKeySeq.name: solResetBladeKeySeq
solResetBladeKeySeq.description: This is the keystroke sequence used to reset the blade while in SOL session console. This sequence must have at least one character. The caret symbol (^) has a special meaning in this sequence. It denotes 'Ctrl' for keystrokes that map to Ctrl sequences (for example, ^[ for the escape key and ^M for carriage return). All occurrences of ^ will be interpreted as part of a Ctrl sequence. Refer to an ASCII-to-key conversion table for a complete list of Ctrl sequences. The default value for this field is '^[R^[r^[R' i.e. ESC R ESC r ESC R.

solBladeName.name: solBladeName
solBladeName.description: The name of the blade as a null terminated string.

solBladeEnable.name: solBladeEnable
solBladeEnable.description: Disable or enable a SOL on a blade.

solBladeIpAddr.name: solBladeIpAddr
solBladeIpAddr.description: This is deprecated in favor of solBladeIpAddr6. IP address of the blade derived from the IP address range for the blade system management processors on the blades. NOTE: The IPv6 address for a blade can be view with the bladeIPv6AddressTable.

solBladeSessionStatus.name: solBladeSessionStatus
solBladeSessionStatus.description: Status of a blade SOL session: solSessionNotReady: no SOL session connected to the blade. solSessionReady: there is an SOL session to the blade. solSessionActive: there is an SOL session to the blade and there is a client using the SOL session.

solBladeCapability.name: solBladeCapability
solBladeCapability.description: Display whether or not the blade support SOL feature.

solBladeConsoleLoginFrom.name: solBladeConsoleLoginFrom
solBladeConsoleLoginFrom.description: The location information from where the SOL console is logged in.

solBladeConsoleLoginStart.name: solBladeConsoleLoginStart
solBladeConsoleLoginStart.description: The time that SOL console starts.

solBladeConsoleLoginEnd.name: solBladeConsoleLoginEnd
solBladeConsoleLoginEnd.description: The time that SOL console ends.

cinsSupported.name: cinsSupported
cinsSupported.description: Number of Chassis Internal Network (CIN) definitions supported. Currently a maximum of 14 CIN definitions can be supported.

cinGlobalEnable.name: cinGlobalEnable
cinGlobalEnable.description: Disable/Enable Chassis Internal Network (CIN) function dynamically. Enabled: MM reads the CIN entries. For each enabled entry, - If the CIN VLAN ID is new and does not have a CIN interface created yet then create a new CIN interface based on that CIN VLAN ID. Use the CIN IP address from the entry to create a host route. - If the CIN IP address is 0.0.0.0 then start ARP monitoring. Disabled: - Stop all ARP monitoring. - Delete all host routes. - Delete all CIN interfaces.

cinDefExists.name: cinDefExists
cinDefExists.description: Indicates if a Chassis Internal Network (CIN) definition exists for this index or not.

cinDelete.name: cinDelete
cinDelete.description: Delete Chassis Internal Network (CIN) definition. Works like CIN entry disabled. However, the entry is also deleted. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object. Deleting a non-defined entry does nothing.

cinEnable.name: cinEnable
cinEnable.description: Disable or enable a Chassis Internal Network (CIN) definition. Enabled: MM reads the entry and creates a new CIN interface if the CIN VLAN ID is new and does not have a CIN interface created yet, adds host route, and monitors communication path. Start ARP monitoring if IP is 0.0.0.0. Disabled: Delete host route. If this is the last IP address that uses the CIN interface, - Stop ARP monitoring if IP is 0.0.0.0. - Delete the CIN interface if there is no other entry depends on it.

cinId.name: cinId
cinId.description: This is the Chassis Internal Network (CIN) Virtual LAN (VLAN) ID for the internal management network between the Management Module, I/O Module, and the blade OS. The range of valid CIN VLAN IDs is 3 to 4094 (inclusive). This value cannot be the same as the Serial Over LAN (SOL) or Concurrent KVM (cKVM) VLAN ID. NOTE: If creating a new CIN definition, you must define cinId before you define cinIpAddress. NOTE: Before changing this value on an existing CIN definition, you must first disable the definition.

cinIpAddress.name: cinIpAddress
cinIpAddress.description: Chassis Internal Network (CIN) IP address. Restrictions: - CIN entries cannot have matching IP addresses, with the exception of 0.0.0.0. - Multiple IP addresses of 0.0.0.0 with different VLAN IDs are allowed. - The IP address cannot be multi-cast. - The IP address cannot match the MM IP address. - If the CIN IP address is 0.0.0.0, the blade IP address for CIN which is configured in the blade's OS can not be in the same subnet as that of MM. NOTE: If creating a new CIN definition, you must define cinId before you define cinIpAddress. NOTE: Before changing this value on an existing CIN definition, you must first disable the definition. NOTE: When ipv6 is enable on one interface, this column will display all zero IPv4 address

cinIpv6Address.name: cinIpv6Address
cinIpv6Address.description: Chassis Internal Network (CIN) IPv6 address NOTE: When ipv4 is enable on one interface,this column will display all zero IPv6 address.

cinStatusTable.name: cinStatusTable
cinStatusTable.description: Table of Chassis Internal Network (CIN) status entry information.

cinStatusEntry.name: cinStatusEntry
cinStatusEntry.description: Chassis Internal Network (CIN) status table entry.

cinStatusIndex.name: cinStatusIndex
cinStatusIndex.description: The Chassis Internal Network (CIN) status log index number. For consistent results, view as a table and not as individual entries.

cinStatusString.name: cinStatusString
cinStatusString.description: Status of a Chassis Internal Network (CIN) connection. For example: Index:1 VLANID:4094 IPADDR:192.168.70.100 MAC:01:0A:0B:00:01:01 Type:Learned Status:Operational Index is the status entry number in the status table. Followed by the VLAN ID, IP address, and MAC address that the Management Module is communicating with on the CIN connection. Type is either 'Configured' or 'Learned'. Learned implies that the Management Module dynamically discovered the IP address. Configured means that the address was explicitly configured in the Management Module. Status can be 'Operational', 'Not Operational', or 'Disabled'. 'Operational' means the Management Module can ping the CIN IP address. 'Not Operational' means that the Management Module cannot ping the CIN IP address. Verify that the blade and I/O Module are configured properly and that their configurations are compatible with the Management Module. The blade OS also needs to have an IP host route defined (e.g. route add -host 192.168.70.100 eth0.4094). I/O Modules need to have a VLAN defined containing the blade's and the MM's port. Blade and I/O Modules need to be powered up and operational. 'Disabled' means that the CIN configuration has been disabled by a Management Module administrator. For consistent results, view as a table and not as individual entries.

restartSPImmediately.name: restartSPImmediately
restartSPImmediately.description: Restart the MM immediately. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

restartStandbyMM.name: restartStandbyMM
restartStandbyMM.description: Restarts the Standby MM from the Primary MM. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object. NOTE: This mib object is only applicable to systems with a standby MM.

switchOverRedundantMM.name: switchOverRedundantMM
switchOverRedundantMM.description: Switch over to the redundant Management Module. The failover will not occur if the standby or primary MM is in flashing mode. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object. NOTE: This mib object is only applicable to systems with a redundant MM.

resetSPConfigAndRestart.name: resetSPConfigAndRestart
resetSPConfigAndRestart.description: Will cause all the MM information to be reset to it's initial factory defaults (all previous configuration information is lost) and the MM will be re-started. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

resetSPConfigAndRestartSaveLogs.name: resetSPConfigAndRestartSaveLogs
resetSPConfigAndRestartSaveLogs.description: Will cause all the MM information to be reset to it's initial factory defaults (all previous configuration information is lost) and the MM will be re-started. The logs will be saved. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

bladePolicyControlTable.name: bladePolicyControlTable
bladePolicyControlTable.description: Table of blade power policy control information. Contains power on/off enablement status for each blade.

policyControlBladeExists.name: policyControlBladeExists
policyControlBladeExists.description: Indicates whether the server blade specified exists or not.

policyControlBladePowerState.name: policyControlBladePowerState
policyControlBladePowerState.description: The power state for blade. 0 = off, 1 = on, 3 = standby, 4 = hibernate, 255 = unknown.

policyControlBladeHealthState.name: policyControlBladeHealthState
policyControlBladeHealthState.description: The system health state for the blade. Unknown: Blade is in an undefined state. Good: Blade is operating normally. Warning: One or more outstanding warnings exist for this blade. Critical: One or more outstanding critical events for this blade. Kernel Mode: Blade is in kernel mode. Discovering: The MM is currently in the process of discovering this blade. Communications Error: The MM failed to communicate with this blade. No Power: No power to the blade's domain. Flashing: Flashing in progress. Initialization Failure: Blade failed to initialized. Insufficient Power: Not enough power is left in the blade's domain to power the blade. Power Denied: Power was denied to the blade.

policyControlBladeName.name: policyControlBladeName
policyControlBladeName.description: The name of the blade as a null terminated string.

policyLocalPowerControlEnable.name: policyLocalPowerControlEnable
policyLocalPowerControlEnable.description: Blade local power policy control enablement status.

policyWakeOnLanControlEnable.name: policyWakeOnLanControlEnable
policyWakeOnLanControlEnable.description: Blade Wake On LAN enablement status. If WOL is not supported by the blade, it displays 'notApplicable' and WOL can not be enabled or disabled.

bladePolicyLocalPowerControlEnable.name: bladePolicyLocalPowerControlEnable
bladePolicyLocalPowerControlEnable.description: Blade local power control enablement status policy.

bladePolicyWakeOnLanControlEnable.name: bladePolicyWakeOnLanControlEnable
bladePolicyWakeOnLanControlEnable.description: Blade Wake On LAN enablement status policy. The notApplicable(255) enumeration is not valid for SET operations. NOTE: Value returned for the GET command is meaningless for this MIB object.

bladeExists.name: bladeExists
bladeExists.description: Indicates whether the server blade specified exists or not.

bladePowerState.name: bladePowerState
bladePowerState.description: Indicates the power state of the blade specified.

bladeHealthState.name: bladeHealthState
bladeHealthState.description: The system health state for the blade. Unknown: Blade is in an undefined state. Good: Blade is operating normally. Warning: One or more outstanding warnings exist for this blade. Critical: One or more outstanding critical events for this blade. Kernel Mode: Blade is in kernel mode. Discovering: The MM is currently in the process of discovering this blade. Communications Error: The MM failed to communicate with this blade. No Power: No power to the blade's domain. Flashing: Flashing in progress. Initialization Failure: Blade failed to initialized. Insufficient Power: Not enough power is left in the blade's domain to power the blade. Power Denied: Power was denied to the blade.

bladeName.name: bladeName
bladeName.description: The name of the blade as a null terminated string.

bladeRemotePowerEnable.name: bladeRemotePowerEnable
bladeRemotePowerEnable.description: Remote power state for the blade.

bladeConnectionType.name: bladeConnectionType
bladeConnectionType.description: Connection type of the expansion card number one.

bladeRemoteWakeOnLanEnable.name: bladeRemoteWakeOnLanEnable
bladeRemoteWakeOnLanEnable.description: Remote wake on LAN state for the blade.

bladeServerExpansion.name: bladeServerExpansion
bladeServerExpansion.description: This shows whether this blade has an expansion board attached. A yes column indicates that an expansion board is installed for this blade.

bladeWidth.name: bladeWidth
bladeWidth.description: The width of the blade including any supplement blade attached to it

bladeServerExpansion2.name: bladeServerExpansion2
bladeServerExpansion2.description: This shows whether this blade has an expansion board attached. A yes column indicates that an expansion board is installed for this blade.

bladeConnectionType2.name: bladeConnectionType2
bladeConnectionType2.description: Connection type of the expansion card number 2.

bladeConnectionType3.name: bladeConnectionType3
bladeConnectionType3.description: Connection type of the expansion card number 3.

bladeConnectionType4.name: bladeConnectionType4
bladeConnectionType4.description: Connection type of the expansion card number 4.

bladeConnectionType5.name: bladeConnectionType5
bladeConnectionType5.description: Connection type of the expansion card number 5.

bladeHighSpeedConnectionType.name: bladeHighSpeedConnectionType
bladeHighSpeedConnectionType.description: Connection type of the high speed expansion card number 1.

bladeIOCompatibility.name: bladeIOCompatibility
bladeIOCompatibility.description: I/O compatibility status for the blade. The possible values and their meanings are as follows: unknown: This indicates a communication error for the blade. ok: This is the normal (good) case where the blade and the corresponding I/O modules it is internally wired to have no compatibility issues. noIOMs: This means there are no I/O modules in any of the corresponding I/O module bays this blade is internally wired to. attention: This indicates that one or more of the corresponding I/O modules are in communication error. mismatch: This indicates one of the following cases: Fabric types are incompatible An unknown I/O module type An unknown fabric type on the blade

bladeInventoryReady.name: bladeInventoryReady
bladeInventoryReady.description: When a blade management controller or the MM is reset, the blade inventory data is refreshed in the MM database. This includes items like IBM VPD (e.g. - serial number, UUID) and MAC address information. Applications need to know when this information has been populated on the MM before they begin to query it using SNMP or other means. This simple flag object will return a ready or notReady indication for each blade regarding the status of this information. Notes: For blades that are experiencing a 'communication failure' or 'initialization failure' condition, this object will continue to indicate notReady until the condition is resolved. Therefore, any application that polls this object should also incorporate a timeout period.

bladeHealthSummaryTable.name: bladeHealthSummaryTable
bladeHealthSummaryTable.description: Table of blade health summary information. Contains information about the overall blade health status.

temperatureBladeExists.name: temperatureBladeExists
temperatureBladeExists.description: Indicates whether the server blade specified exists or not.

temperatureBladePowerState.name: temperatureBladePowerState
temperatureBladePowerState.description: Indicates the power state of the blade specified.

temperatureBladeName.name: temperatureBladeName
temperatureBladeName.description: The name of the blade as a null terminated string.

temperatureCPU1.name: temperatureCPU1
temperatureCPU1.description: The blade CPU temperature in degrees centigrade(C). An octet string expressed as 'sddd.dd Centigrade' where: s is the sign ('-' for negative or blank space for positive) d is a decimal digit or blank space for leading zeroes. The string 'Not Readable!' indicates that the given monitor is not supported on this system. The string 'No Temperature' indicates that the given monitor does not exist on this system or is powered off.

temperatureCPU2.name: temperatureCPU2
temperatureCPU2.description: The blade CPU temperature in degrees centigrade(C). An octet string expressed as 'sddd.dd Centigrade' where: s is the sign ('-' for negative or blank space for positive) d is a decimal digit or blank space for leading zeroes. The string 'Not Readable!' indicates that the given monitor is not supported on this system. The string 'No Temperature' indicates that the given monitor does not exist on this system or is powered off.

temperatureCPU3.name: temperatureCPU3
temperatureCPU3.description: The blade CPU temperature in degrees centigrade(C). An octet string expressed as 'sddd.dd Centigrade' where: s is the sign ('-' for negative or blank space for positive) d is a decimal digit or blank space for leading zeroes. The string 'Not Readable!' indicates that the given monitor is not supported on this system. The string 'No Temperature' indicates that the given monitor does not exist on this system or is powered off.

temperatureCPU4.name: temperatureCPU4
